    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with a clear emphasis on exploiting favorable matchups against soft pitching. The headline play is undoubtedly **James Wood** (78.42), whose elite matchup against Fuentes (xERA 5.07) and prime leadoff spot anchor our outfield. Similarly, **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) offers massive upside; he benefits from a potent combination of a hitter-friendly park and a slow opposing delivery from Buehler, creating an ideal environment for his speed to thrive. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (71.51) also grades as a tier-one play, as his platoon advantage against Bassitt and the wind blowing out provide a perfect storm for production, making him a high-efficiency anchor in the UTIL spot.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision today was excluding **Kyle Karros** (62.71) in favor of the current lineup structure. While **Kyle Karros** boasts an attractive profile against Buehler, our current starters edge him out on cumulative efficiency metrics. We are also monitoring the heavy risk associated with the Suarez start; while **Jose Caballero** (61.41) gets a boost from a dynamic platoon edge and wind conditions, the matchup remains neutral-to-tricky, much like the decision to start **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (55.26), who is actively hindered by the pitcher's elite hold capabilities despite the wind-aided park factor.\n\nWe are flagging the heavy slate of left-handed pitching today as a potential drag on our stolen base objectives. While **Brice Turang** (61.93) is a vital cog due to his leadoff duties and speed, his score is tempered by the risk of facing Mize. We have intentionally benched **Corbin Carroll** (53.85) today; despite his pedigree, facing a pitcher like Kay (xERA 2.60) presents a sub-optimal path to points compared to the high-volume, low-xERA matchups we are targeting elsewhere. With **Max Muncy** falling below our 40.0 floor, he remains firmly on the bench to preserve our limited game caps for more favorable daily rotations.",
